{"title":"Bayesian Scale Estimation for Monocular SLAM Based on Generic Object Detection for Correcting Scale Drift","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Monocular SLAM produces maps and trajectories at an arbitrary scale and suffers from time-varying scale drift, degrading metric accuracy.","method":"Use a Bayesian filtering framework to estimate a time-varying local scale correction k_k online by fusing generic object detections with class-specific height priors and a motion model of scale drift. The transition p(k_k|k_{k-1}) is Gaussian with variance s_pk proportional to the accumulated camera rotation since the last update (clipped between s_min and s_max), capturing how drift grows with angular motion. When height priors are Gaussian, implement the update as a Kalman filter by marginalizing object height, yielding simple mean/variance prediction-correction steps."},{"problem":"Object detections can include background/occlusions, making naive height-from-bbox unreliable and leading to noisy scale observations.","method":"Define a robust probabilistic observation model that estimates object height from SLAM map points projected inside the detection. Compute a representative 3D point on the object surface by gamma-weighted averaging of depth-ranked points, construct a vertical 3D line through it, and intersect it with back-projected rays from the top/bottom of the detection to get height Ĥ. Form the scale observation as ĸ̂=H/Ĥ and model the likelihood as Gaussian around k_k with standard deviation derived via uncertainty propagation from the depth variance of the selected points."},{"problem":"Need a practical, real-time integration that corrects scale drift during operation and demonstrably improves trajectory accuracy.","method":"Integrate the Bayesian/Kalman scale estimator into ORB-SLAM2, using YOLO9000 detections and a Gaussian prior on car height (mean ~1.5 m). Run updates periodically in real time with negligible overhead. On KITTI, this reduces average relative translation error to ~5.5%, outperforming object-detection-based baselines and showing a large gain over a variant without the motion model (≈3× improvement over prior work)."}]}
